Yes, you absolutely could write it that way. Your version is valid.

What I wrote separates it into two steps:

1. “If I don’t already have a reference, try to find one.”
2. “After that attempt, if I still don’t have one, fail.”

That style is a little easier to read because the second `if (gameplayTilesRoot == null)` means:

“If manual assignment didn’t happen and auto-find didn’t work either, stop.”

Your version puts the error handling directly inside the `else` of `tilesRoot != null`, which is also fine. The main tradeoff is readability.

Your version:
```csharp
if (gameplayTilesRoot == null)
{
    var tilesRoot = GameObject.Find("GameplayTiles");
    if (tilesRoot != null)
    {
        gameplayTilesRoot = tilesRoot.transform;
    }
    else
    {
        Debug.LogError("PlayerController needs a GameplayTiles root reference.", this);
        enabled = false;
        return;
    }
}
```

Mine:
```csharp
if (gameplayTilesRoot == null)
{
    var tilesRoot = GameObject.Find("GameplayTiles");
    if (tilesRoot != null)
    {
        gameplayTilesRoot = tilesRoot.transform;
    }
}

if (gameplayTilesRoot == null)
{
    Debug.LogError("PlayerController needs a GameplayTiles root reference.", this);
    enabled = false;
    return;
}
```

Why I slightly prefer the second one:
- it avoids nesting the failure case deeper
- it checks the final state of `gameplayTilesRoot`, not just the result of one search
- it reads more like “try setup, then validate setup”

So conceptually:
- your version asks: “Did `Find` fail right now?”
- the current version asks: “After everything we tried, is the reference still missing?”

That second idea is often nicer in setup code.

So short answer: yes, your code works, and it’s not wrong. This is mostly a style/readability choice.

